"{\n  \"text\": \"Hi everybody. I've done a bunch of videos on the health benefits of living foods made and grown in living soils. I've done handful of videos about the uh ecological benefits of regenerative farming in terms of uh fixing broken water cycles where the water isn't properly going back into the atmosphere because it is running off of the farmland and into the waterways as opposed to being spread out over the land, it's getting concentrated into the waterways. Done a bunch of those videos. One of the videos I haven't done a lot of is the personal freedom and ability to survive in almost any medium strength uh catastrophe through water uh collection and food preparation of making your own food and one collecting your own water. And I think that if we did these two things as a society, as a culture, if just half of us, three-quarters of us, we could create a sustainability that we don't have under the current situation that we live in. Most people realize that the structures that support our civilization are fragile. And underlying all of this is food and water. If the water should turn off, how many of us could live beyond a week? Uh, not many of us. And in the cities it would be a catastrophe. It would be anarchy and all of these things. And really, this could be fixed by a handful of cheap uh water collection barrels. You know, I I have ones that go uh 300 or 400 gallons and they're $60 used and they're clean. And this isn't i it's just an easy step, you know, to clean that water once it's come off your uh roof. You know, you do have to clean it, you do have to s uh you know clean up the bacteria and all the dangerous stuff that may end in there, but that's not the end of the world. And growing your own food, especially if there's a community of people doing that, supported through individual sales from farmers markets and garden markets and things of that nature, we could really like create a support system under ourselves that we don't have now, and that a lot of people are a little bit scared of. Truthfully, most of us know that in a catastrophe, three days is all the supermarkets have in terms of inventory. Here in Houston, Texas, we have hurricanes and things like that. We see this stuff happening. Where occasionally the supermarkets will empty out, and if you go late, there's no peanut butter left. There's no anything left. Anyway, I think that one of the things that we can do to survive as a species, as a people in a fragile civilization, is go back to the victory garden concept where we grow some of our food, where we collect some of our water, where we do little things so that if something should go catastrophically wrong, it's just the extras that are damaged. It's not our deaths. Anyway, thanks, y'all.\",\n  \"sentences\": [\n    {\n      \"text\": \" Hi everybody.\",\n      \"start\": 1.6,\n      \"end\": 2.72,\n      \"duration\": 1.12,\n      \"confidence\": 0.96,\n      \"tokens\": [\n        {\n          \"text\": \" Hi\",\n          \"start\": 1.6,\n          \"end\": 1.84,\n          \"duration\": 0.24,\n          \"confidence\": 0.907\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \" ever\",\n          \"start\": 2.0,\n          \"end\": 2.16,\n          \"duration\": 0.16,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \"yb\",\n          \"start\": 2.16,\n          \"end\": 2.4,\n          \"duration\": 0.24,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \"ody\",\n          \"start\": 2.4,\n          \"end\": 2.56,\n          \"duration\": 0.16,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \".\",\n          \"start\": 2.56,\n          \"end\": 2.72,\n          \"duration\": 0.16,\n          \"confidence\": 0.901\n        }\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"text\": \" I've done a bunch of videos on the health benefits of living foods made and grown in living soils.\",\n      \"start\": 2.72,\n      \"end\": 9.28,\